post_text: As you may be aware, the exact impact of tomorrow's coastal storm is changing as the day goes on. Honorable mention, Catherine Antonelli, Eisenhower Middle School.

Tentative Agreement Reached

Last night the Board negotiation committee and FTEA reached a tentative agreement which will ensure that Teaching Assistants will continue to be employed by the school district; avoiding any further discussion surrounding outsourcing of Teaching Assistants. The specific terms are still being reviewed and finalized and will not be available for public discussion this evening, however, the main concern over possible outsourcing has been resolved and Teaching Assistants will continue to be employed by the district moving forward.

post_text:
This morning a student found a suspicious item in the hallway at Barkalow Middle School and gave it to his teacher. The teacher reported it to the main office, and the determination was made to err on the side of safety and implement a modified shelter in place. During the shelter-in-place, students and staff were required to remain in their classrooms and continue with typical instructional activities while administrators conducted locker searches.

The modified shelter-in-place lasted approximately ninety minutes. The locker searches did not result in any findings, and the school day proceeded as typical. All students and staff were safe throughout the school day. We are proud of our staff and students for their ability to respond to safety issues appropriately.

post_text: Barkalow achieved their goal! Earlier this week, Barkalow set out to STUFF Mr. Mayer's Suburban with canned and boxed goods as well as paper products for Open Door, Freehold's area food pantry. In addition to being one of Barkalow's beloved teacher assistants, Mr. Mayer donates his time to St. Peter's Thrift Store and other area food pantries. Barkalow's Student Council designed the food drive,Stuff the Suburban, with Mr. Mayer's input. We are all so gracious for his support and for the Barkalow community's generosity. Thanks to all the Suburban is STUFFED and on its way to Open Door to share the donations with Freehold residents in need. Pictured above are Student Council members, Mr. Mayer and his famous Suburban.

Custodial workers are often overlooked in general. However, they provide a much-needed service that most people are not willing to do.

While each of our schools has a "Lead Custodian" that ensures our schools operate seamlessly during the day, the majority of our custodians work in the evening and their work goes unnoticed.

Please take a moment today to say a big thank you to our Custodial Staff who play a major role in keeping our schools running.

THANK YOU TO ALL OF OUR CUSTODIANS!!

post_text: The Freehold Township Education Foundation (FTEF) hosted its second annual fundraiser event at iPlay America to raise funds for its Connect Us! campaign Monday, February 24. The event helped raise approximately $10,100, which will be split 80% to the FTEF (just under $8,100) and 20% to our PTOs (just over $2,000). The family fun night event was attended by 676 pre-K through 8th grade school students and teachers from theFreehold Township School District. The winner of the trophy for the greatest ratio of attendance out of total roster is Laura Donovan, with 136 or 28.1% attendees.
